The economic impact study from 2001 was based on the assumption that the section leading to the border and the section leading by the Bohemian Central Mountains would go under transport at the same time.
At the time of the examination it was obvious that the section by the Bohemian Central Mountains would not be opened to the original date.
This reduces the aforementioned EIRR values.
The costs of both sections at the 31.12.2005 amounted to €897 million excluding VAT, which is 27.4% higher than the economic situation assessment in 2001.
There is also a risk that Section 0805 will get a different more elaborate standard course, which would affect the economic viability of the project.
The economic impact showed that the construction of both sections of motorway is economically justified with a daily traffic volume of at least 18 000 vehicles per day in 2010. The forecast for 2008 had predicted 22 940 cars per day.
However, a study on diversion routes as an alternative to the missing section through the Bohemian mountain range estimates a traffic of 12,600 to 13 750 cars per day in 2007. The project is then below the economic viability limit.
A higher volume of traffic on the routes intended to replace the missing section with the Bohemian low mountain range is highly likely to result in congestion and thus increased external costs, which were resulting in the initial economic analysis. Not taken into account.
The aforementioned reduction in revenue and an increase in costs means that the already low EIRR for the construction of the borderline section of D 8 will not be reached.
The construction of the border section of D 8 is therefore uneconomical.
Cost increases were also achieved during the construction of the A-17, as in the construction of the two two sections of the D 8.
As part of the macroeconomic assessment for the 1992 Federal Transport Plan, the Federal Ministry of Transport assumed investment costs of around €320 million.
In doing so, it determined a benefit/cost ratio of 4.6.
In the meantime, the costs have increased to around €670 million and the pay-to-cost ratio has decreased by more than half.
The BRH had examined the economics of planning and construction of the A 17 motorway, regardless of the parallel tests with the NKcomo between 2003 and 2005.
In doing so, he noted that the authority responsible for the permit called for an unnecessary landscape tunnel for the third section of the A 17.
During the course of the audit, the BRH succeeded in convincing the Federal Ministry and the Road Construction Administration of the superfluousness of the landscape tunnel.
This prevented €10 million in construction costs and €150,000 in annual operating costs.
When examining the first section of the A 17, the BRH found that the construction was inadequately prepared.
The following example illustrates this:
During the planning phase, the road construction administration refrained from recording the condition of the rock on the surface of the Dölzschen wall, as it was difficult to access.
It wasn't until the tunnel drive reached the wall that she made up for it.
This showed that the rock was more weathered than assumed in the tender.
Elaborate measures such as anchorages, injections and rockfall protection nets for around €3.3 million became necessary.
The road construction administration bore not only the cost of additional, already required services, such as securing the damp wall, but also for those that would not have been required in the case of proper construction preparation.
This includes expenses as a result of disrupted construction processes (€3.2 million), additional induction of the propulsion team (€0.5 million) and increased wages and material prices due to the extension of the construction period (€7 million).
This additional expenditure of around €10.7 million is not offset by any lasting added value.
The BRH took these and other measures as an opportunity to call on the Federal Ministry of Germany to better supervisate its professional supervision for large-scale road construction measures.
In this context, it should urge that road authorities introduce quality assurance systems.
The benefits of cooperation for BRH and NKcomo The collaboration met the expectations of both Court of Auditors.
The BRH received insights into the planning, awarding and execution of the construction of the border bridge.
Both Court of Auditors developed a database of bridge and tunnel prices, which will be helpful in future audits.
The NKcomo found that the most important structural parameters for bridges, tunnels and roadways of the D 8 are no different from those of the A 17.
The auditors of both Court of Auditors involved in the cooperation gained valuable experience, which will be useful in future audits.
